A continuous function $f : {\mathbb M} \to {\mathbb R}$ filters ${\mathbb M}$ by sublevel sets 
${\mathbb M}_{\leq r} = \{ x \in {\mathbb M} \; | \; f(x) \leq r \}.$
Apply homology, with coefficients in a field, and the resulting object is called a persistence module.
There are two invariants of the persistence module.
Zomorodian and Carlsson define the \emph{barcode} of a persistence module as the module's list of \mbox{indecomposables \cite{ZC2005}}.
The \emph{persistent homology group}, for each pair of values $r < s$, is the image of the map ${\mathsf{H}}_\ast({\mathbb M}_{\leq r} \subset {\mathbb M}_{\leq s})$.
Cohen-Steiner, Edelsbrunner, and Harer (CSEH) define the \emph{persistence diagram} of a persistence module as a 
visualization of all persistent homology groups \cite{CSEdH}.
By properties of vector spaces and by the shape of a persistence module, 
the two invariants are equivalent.
The persistence diagram, or equivalently the barcode, of a persistence module is a complete invariant of the persistence module.
More importantly, the persistence diagram is stable to $C^0$-perturbations of $f$ making it 
an interesting tool for data analysis.

The persistence diagram is very different in philosophy from the barcode.
The object of this paper is to generalize the persistence diagram of CSEH.
We consider persistence modules valued in any essentially small, abelian, and Krull-Schmidt category ${\mathsf{C}}$.
The category of vector spaces is an example of such a category.
Using a M\"obius inversion formula, we assign to each persistence module ${\mathsf{{F}}}$ a generalized persistence diagram $X$.
Theorem \ref{thm:main} shows semicontinuity of this assignment.
That is, $X$ lives on in the persistence diagram $Y$ of each nearby persistence module ${\mathsf{{G}}}$.
Depending on ${\mathsf{C}}$, $X$ may not be a complete invariant of ${\mathsf{{F}}}$.



